    {
      "id": "1611815e8bdae82c745e9dfceef1f94e18d3e851",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-02 06:26:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nThis is a good start, and this patch should be landed to b2_4 and b2_5 so that they will not have problems with this flag.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "560349fe3c0db28b0aed57d9ea40c123183c6022",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-02 17:11:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nActually, one problem with the master version of this patch compared to the other versions is that master doesn't use this flag at all to check if there are unsupported features in the filesystem. This was removed during the unified target change and needs to be returned.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "049f5d8f41db88776c77abe0200532fc277270c6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-02 19:01:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAndreas, could you explain a bit what functionality is missing in master? I don't see how 2.5 and 2.4 check this particular flag. It is just set during mount on MDT and is set in MDT_INCOMPAT_SUPP. The master has the same behaviour as I can see. Did I miss something?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "bfb23c240ea1d963be70c37ff4c64c1dc30810e6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-03 05:55:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIn b2_4 this is checked when the OST is first mounted:\n\n int ofd_server_data_init()\n {\n        :\n        :\n        if (lsd->lsd_feature_incompat & ~OFD_INCOMPAT_SUPP) {\n                CERROR(\"%s: unsupported incompat filesystem feature(s) %x\\n\",\n                       obd->obd_name,\n                       lsd->lsd_feature_incompat & ~OFD_INCOMPAT_SUPP);\n                GOTO(err_fsd, rc = -EINVAL);\n        }\n }\n\nSo if the OST is mounted but it was modified by a newer version of Lustre to have a feature that it does not understand, then it will refuse to mount the OST.\n\nThis was being hit on 2.5 when a 2.6-mounted OST was downgraded to 2.5 again, per the original bug.  That behaviour was _almost_ correct on the part of 2.5 (refusing to mount an OST with a filesystem that it didn't understand), with the exception that 2.5 DID know how to handle the OBD_INCOMPAT_FID feature already, and that 2.6 shouldn't have set this feature if it hadn't yet started using FID-on-OST (i.e. mounted in DNE mode).\n\nThis patch is half of the fix - allowing the 2.4/2.5/master OST to be mounted with OBD_INCOMPAT_FID on the OST.  The other half is that the OST should get OBD_INCOMPAT_FID set when it starts creating FID_SEQ_NORMAL objects on the OST for DNE.  That will ensure that anyone upgrading to 2.4/2.5 and starting DNE will not be able to downgrade to 2.1 OSTs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "dc25ca2e7a924764cddc37ed175d28fbd74638f9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-03 17:20:49.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
